Purpose

To create generic functions that can read in csv files located online through their urls then process that data before graphing various summaries that can be modified depending on user input.

Data Processing

The only packages needed for this project are tidyverse and should be loaded in beforehand.

library(tidyverse)

We begin by doing all data processing without functions, starting with reading in the csv, converting it to a tibble, sub setting the data to only variables of interest, then pivoting the data frame to long format before finally doing some simple manipulation to create variables for year and educode.

sheet1 <- read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv")
data1 <- sheet1 %>% 
  as_tibble(sheet1) %>% 
  select(Area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>% 
  rename(area_name = Area_name) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = 3:12, names_to = "educode" , values_to ="enrollment") %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(substr(educode,8,9))) %>%
  mutate(year = if_else(year >=80, paste0(19,year),
                  if_else(year <= 80,paste0(200,year), "error"))) %>%
  mutate(educode = substr(educode,1,7))

Function Creation

Now we begin building functions that are capable of doing the above processing.

Function 1

Reads in a data frame, saves it as a tibble, and finally pivots it to long format.

read_and_transpose <- function(df, value = "enrollment"){
  df %>%
    as_tibble(df) %>% 
    select(Area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>% 
    rename(area_name = Area_name) %>% 
    pivot_longer(cols = 3:12, names_to = "educode" , values_to = value)
}

Function 2

Takes the results of function 1 then creates the year and educode variables.

years_and_codes <- function(df){
  df %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(substr(educode,8,9))) %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(if_else(year >=30, paste0(19,year),
                  if_else(year <= 25,paste0(200,year), "error")))) %>%
  mutate(educode = substr(educode,1,7))
}

Function 3

Takes a county data frame and creates the state variable.

get_state <- function(df){
    df %>%
    mutate( state = str_sub(area_name,-2,-1))
}

Function 4

Takes a state data frame and creates the division variable.

get_division <- function(df){
  division1 <- c("CONNECTICUT","MAINE","MASSACHUSETTS","NEW HAMPSHIRE","RHODE ISLAND","VERMONT")
  division2 <- c("NEW JERSEY","NEW YORK","PENNSYLVANIA")
  division3 <- c("ILLINOIS","INDIANA","MICHIGAN","OHIO","WISCONSIN")
  division4 <- c("IOWA","KANSAS","MINNESOTA","MISSOURI","NEBRASKA","NORTH DAKOTA","SOUTH DAKOTA")
  division5 <- c("DELAWARE","FLORIDA","GEORGIA","MARYLAND","NORTH CAROLINA","SOUTH CAROLINA","VIRGINIA","DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA","District of Columbia","WEST VIRGINIA")
  division6 <- c("ALABAMA","KENTUCKY","MISSISSIPPI","TENNESSEE")
  division7 <- c("ARKANSAS","LOUISIANA","OKLAHOMA","TEXAS")
  division8 <- c("ARIZONA","COLORADO","IDAHO","MONTANA","NEVADA","NEW MEXICO","UTAH","WYOMING")
  division9 <- c("ALASKA","CALIFORNIA","HAWAII","OREGON","WASHINGTON")
  df %>% 
    mutate(division = if_else(area_name %in% division1,"New England",
                        if_else(area_name %in% division2, "Mid-Atlantic",
                          if_else(area_name %in% division3, "East North Central",
                            if_else(area_name %in% division4, "West North Central",
                              if_else(area_name %in% division5, "South Atlantic",
                                if_else(area_name %in% division6, "East South Central",
                                  if_else(area_name %in% division7, "West South Central",
                                    if_else(area_name %in% division8, "Mountain",
                                      if_else(area_name %in% division9, "Pacific","ERROR"))))))))))
}

Function 5

Takes the output of function 3 then returns a list with the county and state data frames.

county_and_state <- function(df){
  row_numbers1 <- grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", df$area_name) 
  row_numbers2 <- -row_numbers1 
  county_data <- slice(df,row_numbers1) 
  class(county_data) <- c("county", class(county_data)) 
  state_data <- slice(df,row_numbers2) 
  class(state_data) <- c("state", class(state_data))
  county_data <-get_state(county_data)
  state_data <- get_division(state_data)
  return(list(county = county_data, state = state_data))
}

Wrapper Function

Combines functions 1-5 with the option to override the enrollment variable name to one of the users choosing.

my_wrapper <- function(url, value = "enrollment", ...) {
  a <- read_csv(url)
  b <- read_and_transpose(a, value,...)
  c <- years_and_codes(b, ...)
  d <- county_and_state(c,...)
  return(d)
}

Combination Function

Now, we created a function that takes the results of our wrapper function and merges the county and state data frames from our outputs together as seen below

match_combine <- function(df1,df2){
  county_merge <- bind_rows(df1$county, df2$county)
  state_merge <- bind_rows(df1$state, df2$state)
  return(list(county = county_merge,state = state_merge))
}
wrap_combine <- match_combine(wrap1, wrap2)

Writing Generic Functions for Summarizing

Now we will write two generic functions to summarize our data with one for county level data and one for state level data

Function for Plotting State Data

Takes in a state data frame and the option to change the name of the enrollment variable then graphs mean enrollment by year for each division excluding any that have the value ERROR.

plot.state <- function(df, var_name = "enrollment"){
  new_df <- df %>%
  filter(division != "ERROR") %>%
  group_by(division, year) %>%
  summarize(mean_enrollment = mean(get(var_name)))
  ggplot(new_df, aes(x = year, y = mean_enrollment, color = division)) + geom_line()
}

Function for Plotting County Data

Takes in a county data frame with the options to change the name of the enrollment variable, select the state of interest, specify whether to only show the top or bottom counties, and finally how many counties to graph.

plot.county <- function(df, var_name = "enrollment", state_filter = "NC", value_choice = "top", x = 5 ){
  area_df <- df %>%
  filter(state == state_filter) %>%
  group_by(area_name) %>%
  summarize (mean_enrollment = mean(get(var_name))) %>%
  arrange(case_when(
    value_choice == "top" ~ desc(mean_enrollment),
    value_choice == "bottom" ~ mean_enrollment)) %>%
  slice_head(n = x)
  
  filtered_df <- df %>%
  filter(df$area_name %in% area_df$area_name)
ggplot(filtered_df, aes(x = year, y = get(var_name), color = area_name)) + geom_line()
}

Combining the Wrapper and Plotting Functions together

Using the Two Data Sets Shown Earlier

edu1 <- my_wrapper("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv")
edu2 <- my_wrapper("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv")
edu_merge1 <- match_combine(edu1, edu2)
plot.state(edu_merge1$state)

plot.county(edu_merge1$county, "enrollment", "PA", "top", 7)

plot.county(edu_merge1$county, "enrollment", "PA", "bottom", 4)

plot.county(edu_merge1$county)

plot.county(edu_merge1$county, "enrollment", "MN", "top", 10)
